99
00:06:33,779 --> 00:06:35,742
which is not the normal mode.

100
00:06:36,593 --> 00:06:45,423
of game prototyping, but it is extremely popular and useful in other storytelling mediums.

101
00:06:45,443 --> 00:06:56,775
So in books, before an author spends months or years trying to create, write a story,

102
00:06:57,647 --> 00:06:59,948
they'll often go to an outliner, to some notes,

103
00:07:00,689 --> 00:07:04,091
because they want to do a smaller risk write-up

104
00:07:04,132 --> 00:07:05,493
to see if their narrative,

105
00:07:05,853 --> 00:07:07,534
the narrative that they have planned, makes sense.

106
00:07:08,775 --> 00:07:11,837
In film or TV, now we have a medium

107
00:07:11,857 --> 00:07:13,298
that's a little bit more complicated.

108
00:07:14,447 --> 00:07:16,729
and there are a couple prototypes.

109
00:07:17,110 --> 00:07:18,612
First, there's a script,

110
00:07:18,932 --> 00:07:20,634
which is just getting the ideas down on the page,

111
00:07:20,674 --> 00:07:22,436
seeing if the ideas make sense in themselves,

112
00:07:23,077 --> 00:07:26,180
and then, once you've gotten through that big risk,

113
00:07:26,521 --> 00:07:28,042
you go to the next level of risk.

114
00:07:28,103 --> 00:07:29,044
Do these ideas make sense?

115
00:07:29,304 --> 00:07:29,784
Visually.

116
00:07:30,345 --> 00:07:31,306
You create a storyboard.

117
00:07:32,216 --> 00:07:36,518
In animated films, it's an even more complex medium.

118
00:07:36,838 --> 00:07:39,459
There's so many technical steps between the idea

119
00:07:39,499 --> 00:07:40,439
and the final product.

120
00:07:41,200 --> 00:07:43,861
And basically, it's a much bigger production.

121
00:07:43,921 --> 00:07:46,042
So prototypes get even more important.

122
00:07:46,602 --> 00:07:48,663
Script, storyboard, then an animatic

123
00:07:48,683 --> 00:07:51,264
where you see how this storyboard looks

124
00:07:51,644 --> 00:07:53,625
set up in a camera so that you're not wasting time

125
00:07:53,705 --> 00:07:55,085
on shots that don't matter.

126
00:07:56,406 --> 00:08:00,228
All of these narrative prototypes address huge risks.

127
00:08:01,086 --> 00:08:02,847
and then smaller and smaller risks

128
00:08:03,888 --> 00:08:05,269
that these elaborate ideas

129
00:08:06,290 --> 00:08:07,851
that people have for their stories

130
00:08:08,411 --> 00:08:09,392
only make sense in their head.

131
00:08:10,853 --> 00:08:12,674
So games, as a narrative medium,

132
00:08:14,035 --> 00:08:15,336
are undeniably complex.

133
00:08:15,396 --> 00:08:18,359
They have everything that animated movies have

134
00:08:18,999 --> 00:08:19,379
and more.

135
00:08:19,399 --> 00:08:21,881
You have to make all your pieces from scratch very often

136
00:08:21,961 --> 00:08:23,562
for this very literal presentation.

137
00:08:24,063 --> 00:08:26,685
Turn an idea to art and sound and animation and logic,

138
00:08:27,385 --> 00:08:28,726
but that's not the biggest risk.

139
00:08:29,531 --> 00:08:30,952
in your game narrative.

140
00:08:31,412 --> 00:08:33,613
The biggest risk, and unknown in games,

141
00:08:34,293 --> 00:08:34,933
is the player.

142
00:08:36,494 --> 00:08:40,115
So, if your premise and goals and choices and challenges

143
00:08:40,675 --> 00:08:43,056
don't make sense to the player, if they don't line up,

144
00:08:43,937 --> 00:08:45,517
then you're sunk.

145
00:08:46,498 --> 00:08:49,579
Because the hero is not interested in continuing on this journey.

146
00:08:49,619 --> 00:08:51,480
So let's put the hero in the narrative

147
00:08:51,940 --> 00:08:54,121
as cheaply as possible, as early as we can.

148
00:08:55,081 --> 00:08:55,561
Basically...

149
00:08:56,835 --> 00:09:02,260
I think it's really useful when you're addressing this risk of games as a narrative to create

150
00:09:02,420 --> 00:09:07,905
a narrative prototype, a playable and flexible outline of the premise, the rules, the events

151
00:09:07,966 --> 00:09:13,211
and the choices that's made to answer some really fundamental question of what's the

152
00:09:13,251 --> 00:09:14,392
hero's journey for the player?

153
00:09:15,433 --> 00:09:19,377
Do all your pieces fit together into a compelling experience and does it all make sense?

154
00:09:20,798 --> 00:09:20,998
So

155
00:09:22,448 --> 00:09:26,851
that's a big question that's a really heavy question to try to tackle

156
00:09:27,671 --> 00:09:30,293
uh... and architecting something like that digitally

