00:09:30,753 --> 00:09:33,415
seems to me at least a bit overwhelming uh... because

158
00:09:33,915 --> 00:09:36,537
we want this narrative prototype to be flexible

159
00:09:37,217 --> 00:09:39,099
and to be something that uh...

160
00:09:39,499 --> 00:09:43,301
that players can interact with in a sort of fluid way we wanted to have lots of

161
00:09:43,441 --> 00:09:44,862
small and uh... sort of

162
00:09:45,563 --> 00:09:48,425
address a bunch of the features that you see from your larger game

163
00:09:49,045 --> 00:09:50,946
and uh... respond to the player intelligently

164
00:09:52,187 --> 00:09:57,269
In code, trying to build a prototype like this could itself become a cumbersome and

165
00:09:57,429 --> 00:09:59,991
overreaching mess like Matrix Reloaded.

166
00:10:00,011 --> 00:10:03,312
So that is why.

167
00:10:06,093 --> 00:10:09,035
I suggest doing a narrative prototype on paper.

168
00:10:09,575 --> 00:10:11,537
Paper is quick and easy and disposable.

169
00:10:11,737 --> 00:10:14,119
It allows for improvisation and imagination.

170
00:10:14,819 --> 00:10:17,741
Basically, if your game is a show starring the player,

171
00:10:18,462 --> 00:10:20,023
the easiest way to get them engaged early

172
00:10:20,063 --> 00:10:21,884
is to basically create this little

173
00:10:21,944 --> 00:10:24,846
narrative paper prototype, set up a cardboard TV,

174
00:10:25,687 --> 00:10:27,048
essentially, and invite them inside.

175
00:10:27,248 --> 00:10:30,370
Or put another way, make your narrative outline

176
00:10:30,871 --> 00:10:31,391
as a board game.

